*****************************************************************************
* FPL ***********************************************************************
*****************************************************************************

@Node "Fpl_scripts" "Cybertracker.guide/Fpl Scripts"
@Toc "Main"


 @{u}@{b}Fpl Scripts@{uu}@{ub}

 Frexx Programming Language (FPL) is an interpreting script/macro language
 shared library, designed to be flexible and easy to incorporate in any code.

 FPL is a complete script programming language _very_ similar to C. If you
 are a software developer and plans to add any kind of macro/script control,
 consider the FPL alternative!

 fpl.library lets the software programmer define functions and variables that
 FPL should accept. The library will call a function in the software whenever
 any of these functions are used or variables are read in an FPL program.

 Programmers that want to lern how to code FPL:
    @{" FPL programming        " link "FPLuser.guide/Main" 0} 

 And the list of CyberTracker specific functions :
    @{" FPL CTFunctions        " link FPLfunctions} 

@EndNode

*****************************************************************************

@Node "FPLfunctions" "Cybertracker.guide/Fpl Functions"
@Toc "Fpl_scripts"


 @{u}@{b}Fpl Functions@{uu}@{ub}

 @{u}@{b}openconsole() - opens a CON: on the CyberTracker screen@{uu}@{ub}

	success = openconsole()

	Opens a standard dos console which can be used as an userinterface for
	the FPL script.
	
	See Also: closeconsole() - conwrite() - conread()

 @{u}@{b}closeconsole() - closes the consolewindow @{uu}@{ub}

	void closeconsole()	

	Might be called even if openconsole() never was called.

 @{u}@{b}conwrite() - write a formated string to the consolewindow@{uu}@{ub}

	void conwrite(string,data,data,data,...)

	Works likes the Ansi-C function printf().
	
 @{u}@{b}conread() - read a string from the consolewindow@{uu}@{ub}

	string = conread()

	Returns a string from the console.

 @{u}@{b}getcommand() - get a command from the current pattern@{uu}@{ub}

	command = getcommand(track,pos,cline)

	track - which track
	pos - position in pattern
	cline - which of the 2 command channels.

 @{u}@{b}setcommand() - sets a command in the current pattern@{uu}@{ub}

	void setcommand(track,pos,cline,command)

	track - which track
	pos - position in pattern
	cline - which of the 2 command channels.
	command - the command

	Please consult the example files for more info.


@EndNode

****************************************************************************
* ISS **********************************************************************
****************************************************************************

@Node "iss" "Cybertracker.guide/ISS"
@Toc "Main"


 @{u}@{b}ISS - Independent Sound System@{uu}@{ub}

	This is the heart of Cybertracker. The ISS system in combination
	with the large amount of channels (255) makes it possible to
	create very complex tunes. Actually Cybertracker itself can't
	even play a single tone.

	But first som defenitions: 

	@{u}@{b}Logical Channels@{uu}@{ub}

	When you create a new song you are asked for how many channels
	to use. These are the channels which you can see and where you
	create your song. Just like the old Protrackerstyle.


	@{u}@{b}The Independent Sound Systems@{uu}@{ub}

	These are standard Amiga executables which resides in the iss
	directory in your Cybertracker directory. This makes it very
	easy to add more features to the tracker, and you might even
	write your very own ISS -  How about that? When Cybertracker is
	starded up it searches the iss diretory for all #?.iss files.
	When they all are loaded Cybertracker initializes them. And they
	add all of their ISS channels (see below) to a public list in
	Cybertracker. Notice that none of the ISS Channels is enabled
	which means that no hardware resources is allocated. This means
	for intance that if you have a MIDI ISS it woun't allocate your
	serial.device, if it isn't enabled. Please notice that these files
	isn't executed as a standard Amiga executable. It's more treated
	as some kind of a library.


	@{u}@{b}ISS Channels@{uu}@{ub}
	
	These channels is put together with the logicalchannels
	using the @{" ISS patch bay " Link isspb}. This makes it possible for you to
	use which ISS channels you would at any logical channel you would
	like.
		


	Let's look at two examples:


	Logical channel		ISS Channel

	000			IntCh1
	001			IntCh2
	002			IntCh3
	003			MixCh4/A
	004			MixCh4/B
	005			MixCh4/C
	006			MixCh4/D

	This is a very nice setup which provides you with three nonmixed
	and four mixed channels. I think this soloution is much better
	than the eight channel setup which can for instance be found in
	OctaMED. The main advantages is: Less cpu usage and three channes
	is not altered at all (you loose a 3dB of dynamic range if you
	mix samples with superposition). 


	Logical channel		ISS Channel

	000			IntCh1
	001			IntCh2
	002			IntCh3
	003			IntCh4
	004			Midich0
	005			Midich1
	006			Midich2
	007			Midich3

	This setup is not possible for the moment because i havn't finished
	the midi channels yet, but as you can see it provides you with four
	standard protracker channels and four midi channels (0-3).


	Notes:

      * The channels allocate the soundchannels using the audio.device at
	highest priority (+127). This means that nothing else can steal the
	channels. 

      * If another program already has allocated the channels when Cyber-
	tracker starts up, you will get some anoying requesters from each
	of the ISS channels in the default config that says that the hardware
	is already used by someone else. The Logic Channels will be assigned
	to the Dummy None ISS. The first thing to do now (if you have planes
	to run the tracker) is ofcourse to quit any other program which has
	allocated the audiochannels. Then you might either quit Cybertracker and 
	restart it or enter the @{" ISS patch bay " Link isspb} to connect all
	channels to each other again.



    The following ISS'es is currently present in the Cybertracker 
    distribution archive:

    @{" Standard 4_channels " Link "/iss/int4ch.guide/main" 0}
    @{" Mixed   16_channels " Link "/iss/mix16.guide/main" 0}
    @{" Midi    16_channels " Link "/iss/midi16.guide/main" 0}

@EndNode

****************************************************************************

@Node "isspb" "Cybertracker.guide/ISS Patch Bay"
@Toc "iss"


 @{u}@{b}ISS Patch Bay@{uu}@{ub}

    This patch bay can be found in the Song/Edit Data menu item.


	Let's have a look at some of the gadgets:
                         ___________________
			|@{u}@{b} Current Song      @{uu}@{ub}| (1)

	 (2)			(3)			(4)
  ___________________	 ___________________	 ____________________
 |000: IntCh1      |#|	|None             |#|	|@{" 4 Ch Standard" Link "/iss/int4ch.guide/main" 0}   |#|
 |001: IntCh2      |#|	|IntCh1           |#|	|@{" 16Ch Mixed   " Link "/iss/mix16.guide/main" 0}   |#|
 |002: IntCh3      |#|	|IntCh2           |#|	|@{" Midi 16 ch   " Link "/iss/midi16.guide/main"0}   |#|
 |003: MixCh4/A    |#|	|IntCh3           |#|	|                  |#|
 |004: MixCh4/B    |#|	|IntCh4           |#|	|                  |#|
 |005: MixCh4/C    |#|	|MixCh1/A         |#|	|                  |#|
 |006: MixCh4/D    |#|	|MixCh1/B         |#|	|                  |#|
 |007: Midi 01     |#|	|MixCh1/C         | |	|                  |#|
 |008: Midi 14     |#|	|MixCh1/D         | |	|                  |#|
 |009: Midi 16     |#|	|MixCh2/A         | |	|                  |#|
 |                 |#|	|MixCh2/B         | |	|                  |#|
 |                 |#|	|MixCh2/C         | |	|                  |#|
 |                 |#|	|MixCh2/D         | |	|                  |#|
 |                 |#|	|Midi 01          | |	|                  |#|
 |                 |#|	|Midi 02          | |	|                  |#|
 |                 |#|	|Midi 03          | |	|                  |#|
 |                 |#|	|Midi 04          | |	|                  |#|
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ	 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ     ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ


 1. This cycle gadget selects if you are editing the "current song" setup
    or the default which is save in the environment config.

 2. This is the list of the logic channels.

 3. This is the list of the ISS channels if you press on one of these it
    will be connected to the selected logic channel (2). If it's beeing used
    by another logic channel a requester will pop up with a message saying
    that the channel is busy.

 4. This is the list of the ISSes. You are not able to do anything with them
    in this version.


    ISS Patch bay FAQ:

    Q: Why can't i use IntCh1 and MixCh1/ABCD at the same time ?

    A: Because they are using the same audio hardware. You can find you
       which hardware channel a ISS channel is using by pressing the INFO button
       below the ISSCHlist (3). But a good rule is not to use to ISSchannels which
       have the same Chx code at the same time. For instance IntCh1 and MixCh1/ABCD
       both uses Ch1.

@EndNode
